  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Decide which of the following binary structures are groups. For each, if the binary structure <em>isn't</em> a group, prove that. (Remember, you should <em>not</em> state that inverses do or do not exist for elements until you have made sure that the structure contains an identity element!) If the binary structure <em>is</em> a group, prove that.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\Q</m> under multiplication
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\M_2(\R)</m> under addition
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\M_2(\R)</m> under multiplication
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\R^+</m> under <m>*</m>, defined by <m>a*b=\sqrt{ab}</m> for all <m>a,b\in \R^+</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>

  <solution>
<p>    <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>\Q</m> isn't a group under multiplication since <m>0\in \Q</m> has no inverse.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
     <p>Matrix multiplication is always associative, and the zero matrix in <m>\M_2(\R)</m> acts as an additive identity element.            Finally, let <m>A\in \M_2(\R)</m>.  Then <m>-A\in \M_2(\R)</m> is an inverse for <m>A</m> under addition. Thus, <m>\M_2(\R)</m> is a group under addition.</p>

</li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>\M_2(\R)</m> isn't a group under multiplication since the zero matrix has no inverse.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        <m>1*(4*9)=1*6=\sqrt{6}</m> while <m>(1*4)*9=2*9=\sqrt{18}</m>, so <m>*</m> isn't associative.  Thus, <m>\R^+</m> isn't a group under <m>*</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
    </ol></p>
  </solution>
    </exercise>

