  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>n\in \Z</m>. Prove that <m>n\Z</m> is a group under the usual addition of integers. <em>Note:</em> You may use the fact that <m>\langle n\Z,+\rangle</m> is a binary structure if you provide a reference for this fact.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
    <p>
      We know from <xref ref="nz">Theorem</xref> that <m>\langle n\Z,+\rangle</m> is a binary structure.</p>
<p> Next, <m>+</m> is
            associative on <m>n</m>, since it's associative on
            <m>\Z</m>, and <m>n\Z \subseteq \Z</m>.
          </p>
        <p>            Notice that
            <m>0\in n\Z</m> (since <m>0=n(0)</m>); 0 then clearly acts as
            an identity element for <m>+</m> in <m>n\Z</m>.
          </p>
        <p>Finally, let <m>x\in n\Z</m>, then <m>x=nm</m> for some <m>m\in \Z</m>, so
            <m>-x=n(-m)</m> for <m>m\in \Z</m>, implying <m>-x\in n\Z</m>;
            and clearly <m>-x</m> acts as an inverse for <m>x</m> in
            <m>n\Z</m>.
          </p>
   

    <p>
      Thus, <m>\langle n\Z, +\rangle</m> is a group.
    </p>
  </solution>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>n\in \Z^+</m>. Prove that <m>SL(n,\R)</m> is a group under matrix multiplication.
        <em>Note:</em> You may use the fact that <m>\langle SL(n\R),\cdot\rangle</m> is a binary structure if you provide a reference for this fact.
      </p>
    </statement>
  
  <solution>
    <p>
      We know from <xref ref="sl">Example</xref> that <m>\langle SL(n,\R),\cdot\rangle</m> is a binary structure,and we know that matrix multiplication is always associative. Next, since <m>\det I_n=1</m>, <m>I_n</m> is in <m>SL(n,\R)</m>, and clearly acts as an identity element in <m>SL(n,\R)</m>. Finally, let <m>A\in SL(n,\R)</m>.  Since <m>\det A=1\neq 0</m>, <m>A</m> has an inverse matrix <m>A^{-1}</m> in <m>GL(n, \R)</m>.  <m>A^{-1}</m> is in <m>SL(n,\R)</m> since
            <me> \det(A^{-1})=\frac{1}{\det A}=1/1=1.</me>
            So <m>A</m> has an inverse in <m>SL(n,\R)</m>.
          </p>
    <p>
      Thus, our proof is complete.
    </p>
  </solution>
  </exercise>

